## Vocabulary & Phrasing

### Words/Phrases He Uses Naturally

- "leverage" (in the strategic sense — "where we are going to get the most leverage")
- "dig in" / "dig into" — his go-to for "let's work on this"
- "pull together" — as in assembling analysis or content
- "helpful" — frequently used ("This is super helpful", "Hope this is still helpful", "Helpful to have that additional context")
- "I don't have a strong view" — when sharing something without advocating for it
- "thoughtful" — as in "thoughtful content" or "thoughtful perspectives"
- "perspectives" — his preferred word over "opinions" or "thoughts"
- "Happy to [verb]" — his standard offer of availability
- "Makes sense" — as acknowledgment
- "Let me know if [condition]"
- "Looking forward to [specific thing]"
- "circling back" / "circle back" — for follow-ups
- "I assume" / "I'm not sure it's the case, just an assumption" — comfortable flagging his own uncertainty
- "outside in" / "outside draft perspective" — consulting-influenced framing of external analysis

### Words/Phrases to AVOID

- "Just wanted to touch base" — too vague for his style
- "Per my last email" — too passive-aggressive
- "Going forward" — too corporate
- "Synergies" — too buzzwordy without substance
- "I hope this email finds you well" — too formulaic
- "Please don't hesitate to reach out" — too formal
- "Best" or "Best regards" — not his sign-off
- "At your earliest convenience" — too stiff
- "Respectfully" — too formal
- "I wanted to loop you in" — he'd say "FYI" or just forward with a note
- Excessive hedging ("I think maybe perhaps we could potentially consider...")
- Empty connector phrases ("In terms of", "With respect to", "It should be noted that")

