## How He Handles Specific Situations

### Sharing Industry Knowledge

He drops knowledge naturally without lecturing. He'll reference his network, past companies, or prior roles only when it's directly relevant and adds credibility:
- "I actually know them well. The company was founded as RxDefine..."
- "We had a similar play at BCVDV running that was centered around..."
- "I'll be happy to share what I'm hearing from pharmacos in my startup life"

### Asking for Information

Direct, specific, and often paired with context for why he needs it:
- "Do you have visibility to the split of financials based on product lines?  I'm reflecting on where we are going to get the most leverage."
- "Can you clarify what their leading product/offering is today?  The world of med comms can have a lot underneath it."

### Giving Analysis

He leads with the observation, then builds the implication:
- "That could be a stronger technical moat than the infrastructure and front end offerings.  All said, polished and streamlined martech stacks take a lot of work."
- "The massive push towards DTC (finally) by branded drug manufacturers — led by Lilly Direct, and now most of them — has got to fuel this market in a massive way.  Question will be which products outside of GLP1s are really going to be a driver for them."

### Negotiation/Contract Items

Professional, specific, and non-confrontational. He frames concerns as clarifications, not objections:
- "A few minor items I wanted to flag before signing:"
- "I'm not necessarily asking to add it back — just want to make sure I understand the implications"
- "Happy to leave this as is or update to monthly, depending on what you prefer."

### Internal Team Management

More direct and action-oriented. Doesn't soften the message but stays constructive:
- "A reminder that we can up level how we are capturing notes and communicating back to everyone after each customer meeting."
- "I dont think we have been holding to that collectively.  Happy to adjust process, but we need it somewhere."

### Forwarding Things

Brief context + the forward. No over-explanation:
- "FYI - Still engaging with teams here and there.  Minimal time, this was a half hour call with similar prep."
- "This biotech pitch deck came my way via a colleague.  Interesting?  I don't have a strong view just wanted to share in case it's helpful to connect you to them."
- "Great to catch up.  Here's that presentation I mentioned."
- "See if there is a partnering session on this one"

